35:55.460 --> 35:57.480
and was likely built by the Sumerians

35:57.480 --> 35:59.830
around 5,500 years ago.

36:05.060 --> 36:08.050
At the waste management facility in Altamont,

36:08.050 --> 36:10.420
This is like the weirdest sport ever.

36:10.930 --> 36:11.900
Aah, sorry.

36:11.920 --> 36:15.540
It's like bowling towards a hoosier with witches' hats.

36:15.800 --> 36:17.440
I don't know what you would call that.

36:17.600 --> 36:21.870
the Mythbusters are making the earth move for Jamie's big idea.

36:22.320 --> 36:24.220
It looks great from here, Jamie.

36:24.990 --> 36:25.950
Good.

36:26.690 --> 36:27.470
Let's face it.

36:27.470 --> 36:30.600
there's a very good reason they don't put square wheels on cars.

36:30.650 --> 36:32.010
Come on! Faster!

36:33.810 --> 36:36.060
But you know that started me thinking,

36:36.210 --> 36:37.720
maybe there are circumstances

36:37.730 --> 36:40.040
where square wheels would be the best thing.

36:40.040 --> 36:42.410
Like what if you had a really steep hill

36:42.410 --> 36:44.540
covered with loose dirt that you wanted to climb?

36:44.540 --> 36:46.650
That is where this comes in!

36:46.650 --> 36:49.690
A smooth slope leading to an almost vertical wall

36:49.690 --> 36:51.460
and filled with loose dirt.

36:51.460 --> 36:54.720
This is the ultimate testing ground to compare the efficacy

36:54.730 --> 36:57.880
of square wheels versus round wheels.

36:58.200 --> 37:01.690
50 feet high and with varying degrees of steepness,

37:02.060 --> 37:03.350
This ought to be fun.

37:03.350 --> 37:06.690
this hill has exactly the kind of off-road conditions

37:06.690 --> 37:10.460
for the ultimate test of the Mythbusters' square wheels.

37:10.460 --> 37:12.440
Here's how this test is gonna go.

37:12.490 --> 37:14.770
First we're gonna take the truck with its round wheels,

37:14.780 --> 37:17.720
I'm gonna drive it up that slope as far as we can make it.

37:17.730 --> 37:20.140
Let's say we make it about halfway up.

37:20.140 --> 37:23.260
Editors, will you give me a dotted line halfway up the slope?

37:23.420 --> 37:24.390
Thank you.

37:24.560 --> 37:27.090
Then we're gonna bolt the square wheels to the truck,

37:27.090 --> 37:29.120
and we're going to take the same slope

37:29.120 --> 37:30.940
and see if we can make it farther.

37:31.220 --> 37:35.700
If we can, we have literally reinvented the wheel.

37:36.080 --> 37:37.300
Well, I think everything's in place.

37:37.300 --> 37:39.360
Shall we suit up and do the round-wheel test?

37:39.360 --> 37:40.930
- I don't see why not. - All right.

37:40.930 --> 37:43.780
If we can't, we've just proven what we already suspected:

37:43.820 --> 37:45.330
square wheels are stupid.

37:46.280 --> 37:47.850
It's a simple plan,

37:47.850 --> 37:48.850
You ready?

37:49.120 --> 37:50.170
I am now.

37:50.480 --> 37:52.700
and it all comes down to Jamie's theory

37:52.700 --> 37:56.890
on why square wheels could work better on loose ground.

37:56.890 --> 37:58.320
When it comes to soft surfaces,

37:58.320 --> 37:59.590
the thing about round wheels

37:59.590 --> 38:02.250
is that all of the weight of the vehicle

38:02.250 --> 38:04.930
is right here where it contacts the ground.

38:05.080 --> 38:07.370
The PSI. There is very high.

38:07.370 --> 38:11.260
That means that it will easily sink through soft stuff and get buried.

38:11.260 --> 38:13.850
Also, as it tries to roll forward,

38:13.850 --> 38:17.060
it tends to plow that soft stuff ahead of it,

38:17.060 --> 38:19.470
which makes it hard to climb out of things.

38:19.470 --> 38:23.850
And that's why in things like sand or snow or loose dirt

38:23.850 --> 38:24.910
And we're stuck.

38:24.910 --> 38:26.080
you get stuck.

38:26.500 --> 38:28.120
On the other hand, our square wheel

38:28.120 --> 38:30.910
has this entire surface contacting the ground,

38:30.910 --> 38:34.380
which means that the PSI is gonna be a small fraction

38:34.380 --> 38:36.510
of what it would be under a round tire.

38:36.610 --> 38:38.420
And then when you try to move forward,

38:38.420 --> 38:40.800
instead of just plowing into the dirt,

38:40.850 --> 38:42.910
it's gonna actually cut into it

38:42.910 --> 38:46.380
and actually lever the whole vehicle ahead.

38:46.380 --> 38:47.890
At least that's the theory.

38:49.050 --> 38:50.240
That's the theory.

38:50.240 --> 38:52.250
So it's time to get trucking.

38:52.400 --> 38:55.240
Round-wheel, hill-climbing control test.

38:55.300 --> 38:58.490
In 3, 2, 1.

39:06.990 --> 39:08.410
You think that's as high as you can go?

39:08.410 --> 39:09.460
I think so.

39:10.900 --> 39:12.490
That's pretty darn high!

39:13.980 --> 39:14.970
Halfway up the hill,

39:14.970 --> 39:17.860
and the round wheels can't get a grip on the loose earth.

39:17.860 --> 39:20.460
So the benchmark to beat has been set,

39:20.720 --> 39:21.950
What do we do now?

39:22.340 --> 39:23.170
I don't know.

39:23.170 --> 39:24.280
Back down slowly?

39:24.280 --> 39:26.640
Well, if I can.

39:26.640 --> 39:29.820
which means the Mythbusters must return to the start line

39:31.550 --> 39:33.080
That is intense.

39:33.090 --> 39:34.780
and swap out the wheels.

39:36.100 --> 39:36.900
It's on.

39:37.030 --> 39:38.300
It's like one of those

39:38.300 --> 39:40.690
"What are we doing?" moments.

39:41.050 --> 39:42.590
Our round wheels got us about

39:42.590 --> 39:45.650
halfway up the loose dirt on the steep part.

39:45.830 --> 39:48.360
Now, we're never gonna get all the way up

39:48.370 --> 39:50.660
because, well, it's vertical up there

39:50.660 --> 39:51.870
and we just can't do that.

39:51.870 --> 39:53.440
But the square wheels --

39:53.580 --> 39:55.900
I think they're gonna get us most of the way there.

39:56.150 --> 39:59.530
This is square wheels, the final hill climb.

39:59.810 --> 40:02.750
In 3, 2, 1.

40:02.750 --> 40:03.850
Go!

40:05.180 --> 40:07.070
Oh, yeah. Come on, baby.

40:08.890 --> 40:09.790
Yes!

40:09.790 --> 40:11.350
Yes! Yes!

40:11.350 --> 40:13.280
Go! Break that rope!

40:13.280 --> 40:14.750
Break it! Yeah!

40:14.750 --> 40:17.570
Come on! Faster! Go a little more!

40:17.750 --> 40:20.190
Oh! No.

40:21.060 --> 40:22.400
Just like the round wheels,

40:22.400 --> 40:24.060
the spinning square wheels

40:24.060 --> 40:26.250
can't get purchase on the loose ground.

40:26.250 --> 40:28.310
All right. We're going up real slow now.

40:28.310 --> 40:30.010
Hill climbing in square wheels.

40:30.050 --> 40:31.110
Go.

40:31.120 --> 40:32.220
So for take two,

40:32.230 --> 40:35.000
the Hyneman goes for a slow and steady approach.

40:35.000 --> 40:36.230
This is promising.

40:44.850 --> 40:46.130
We're moving forward.

40:46.230 --> 40:47.660
We are moving forward.

40:52.150 --> 40:53.190
You know what?

40:53.300 --> 40:54.220
What?

40:54.230 --> 40:55.670
I don't think they're working.

40:55.680 --> 40:57.790
I don't think they're working either.

40:57.830 --> 40:59.430
We tied at best.

40:59.430 --> 41:00.760
We touched the tape.

41:00.930 --> 41:03.990
It seems the Mythbusters had to reinvent the wheel

41:03.990 --> 41:06.830
to discover that square wheels are just too...

41:07.000 --> 41:08.390
well, square.

41:09.690 --> 41:12.780
Well, that was fricking spectacular.

41:14.880 --> 41:17.450
We start climbing the hill. I'm feeling really good.

41:17.450 --> 41:21.960
I can only imagine the volume rooster tail of dust we're kicking up.

41:21.960 --> 41:24.150
We get up to the tape! We're touching the tape!

41:24.150 --> 41:25.600
I'm thinking, "We're gonna break the tape!"

41:25.600 --> 41:27.020
More! More!

41:27.020 --> 41:28.870
And then we just stayed stationary.

41:28.870 --> 41:31.930
We made it exactly as far up this hill

41:31.980 --> 41:33.800
as we did in our round wheels.

41:33.810 --> 41:36.420
I can't think of any better test to donstrate

41:36.420 --> 41:40.470
that there is really a specific advantage to the square tires.

41:40.470 --> 41:41.650
Well, there you have it.

41:41.650 --> 41:42.950
At best our square wheels

41:42.950 --> 41:46.460
did the same job the round wheels did on this course.

41:46.930 --> 41:48.920
I got to say I'm disappointed in it, though,

41:48.920 --> 41:52.900
because I really think there's something to these wheels.

41:52.900 --> 41:55.870
There may be other environments out there

41:55.870 --> 41:58.990
where they would actually prove superior to round wheels.

41:58.990 --> 42:02.420
But as of this point, they're not.

42:03.610 --> 42:04.770
So, how do you want to call this?

42:04.770 --> 42:06.990
Do square wheels give you a smooth ride?

42:06.990 --> 42:09.160
Well, as ridiculous as it may seem,

42:09.160 --> 42:11.090
I think we got to call that one plausible.

42:11.090 --> 42:12.290
What about hill climbing?

42:12.290 --> 42:13.870
That one, not so much.

42:13.880 --> 42:15.360
The square wheels didn't provide

42:15.360 --> 42:18.110
any kind of significant advantage over the round wheels.

42:18.110 --> 42:19.750
Yeah, well, what are you gonna do?

42:19.750 --> 42:21.030
You want to drive back to the shop?

42:21.040 --> 42:23.830
No, let's walk. It's more comfortable.

42:24.950 --> 42:27.170
OK, I think this is the last time we see square wheels.

42:27.520 --> 42:28.880
Not by long shot.

